article.headline: Middle Tennessee State plays tough in second half
article.linkText: Big first half carries No. 6 Alabama to victory
article.story: TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) -- Alabama coach Mark Gottfried was expecting a tough game from Middle Tennessee State, and he got it. Erwin Dudley had 17 points, 10 rebounds and three blocked shots as the Crimson Tide (No. 6 ESPN/USA Today; No. 4 Associated Press) beat the Blue Raiders 80-65 Monday night. ''That's a good win,'' Gottfried said. ''I was concerned with this game. As I watched them on film, my guard was up. We had to play very hard.'' The Crimson Tide (3-0) led by 22 points with 4:20 left before emptying the bench. Mo Williams had 14 points and five assists, while Kenny Walker also scored 14 points. Emmett Thomas shot 4-for-6 on 3-pointers for 12 points off the bench as Tide reserves accounted for 27 points. Middle Tennessee outscored Alabama 40-38 in the second half. ''I think everybody realizes that we got beat by a very good team,'' said Kermit Davis, in his first year as coach of the Blue Raiders. ''I was very pleased by our effort. We're trying to build a program, so we set a goal to win a 20-minute half. That's progress for us at Middle Tennessee.'' Alabama forced 21 turnovers but only scored 18 points off them and struggled to get into a rhythm offensively. The Tide was outrebounded 42-34 by the Blue Raiders (0-2). Dudley, the reigning Southeastern Conference player of the year, had his best scoring output after getting 12 points in each of the Tide's first two outings. Steven Jackson came off the bench for 15 points in 20 minutes for Middle Tennessee, shooting 7-for-9. Tommy Gunn hit four 3-pointers and had 14 points, while William Pippen added 10 points. Gunn and Pippen each had eight rebounds. ''They were very physical on the inside,'' Jackson said. ''We thought we could match their (toughness), but we didn't do that.'' The Blue Raiders closed to 13 points three times in the second half, the final one on Gunn's 3-pointer and a layup by Napoleon Rhodes to make it 63-50 with 7:52 left. For the second consecutive time, Thomas hit a 3-pointer to stretch it to 16. Dudley blocked a pair of shots on the other end to spark a quick 11-2 run for Alabama and Earnest Shelton capped it with a 3-pointer from the left corner before the Tide reserves took over. ''They tried to play us a little tough to see if we backed down,'' Walker said. Thomas said the well-rounded scoring production makes it tougher for opponents to prepare for the Tide. ''That makes us a lot better,'' said Thomas, a junior college transfer who had nine total points in the first two games. ''It'll be on the scouting report that we spread it out.'' Alabama made 18 of 23 free throws and had 10 steals. The Tide took its biggest lead of the first half, 42-25, on Terrance Meade's free throw with 5.4 seconds left. Alabama made up for an out-of-sync offense at times in the first half by forcing 11 turnovers and shooting 5-for-11 on 3-pointers. The Blue Raiders didn't score in the final 2:55 of the half.
